The bird is a symbol of rapid ascent, of something that needs and desires to be ahead of its time, to show spiritual growth. Birds must also be light, able to throw off burdens. The bird is thus in opposition to the spirit of heaviness. The flock of doves is precisely chosen because it is a conventional symbol of gentleness and peace but combined with the bird’s lightness and need for the ascent, and this is unlike a herd of sheep or cows, say. The dove image also has significant biblical echoes. 

<|endoftext|>

The eagle (Adler) is the most common bird mentioned in N. The most famous use of the eagle is the symbol of a healthy and honest pride. The eagle can view things as beneath it; this is both a specific comprehensive sight which is not an abstraction and honest pride. The snake is cleverness. The combination of these animals (the eagle carrying the snake) is something rare: those who have pride do not understand themselves; those who are clever tend to be self-loathing. It seems likely that they are both derived from the image of a serpent, though the eagle is also the figure of someone who is supposed to be dancing in a hallucination. The snake is cleverness. The combination of these animals (the snake) is something that is both a specific and careful distinction, one that might allow someone like them to show their human form more genuinely, and one that might allow their animal form to show the human it is supposed to be dancing in. This cleverness could be because, in the above sense, the snake is already a snake: it is also a type of streak of lightning. The lightning never goes out of style, never even goes out of the realm of chance. Instead, the eagle and its association with the figure of Dionysus, it is the opposite of that which is supposed to be disciplined, continuous, and without resets. Thus, the snake is supposed to be able to see the light of reason. Indeed, the eagle is already considered as having the strength to stare at nothing but the light of day. Its happiness lies in relishing the terror of the great heights and the abyss, rather than in ignorance of that terror. 

